{{Infobox civil conflict | title = Hells Canyon massacre | partof = [[Anti-Chinese violence in Oregon]] | image = Snake-river-near-dug-bar-hells-canyon-07242011-rogermpeterson (6096632223).jpg | caption = [[Hells Canyon]] and the [[Snake River]], near Dug Bar (2011) | date = May 27, 1887 - May 28, 1887<ref name=NYT-AP95>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/08/20/us/files-found-in-oregon-detail-massacre-of-chinese.html |title=Files Found in Oregon Detail Massacre of Chinese |author= |agency=The Associated Press |date=20 August 1995 |newspaper=The New York Times |accessdate=25 April 2018}}</ref> | place = [[Chinese Massacre Cove]], [[Wallowa County, Oregon|Wallowa County]], [[Oregon]], [[United States]] | coordinates = {{coord|45.7797222|-116.6650000}} | causes = Gold theft, racism | goals = Gold theft | methods = [[ambush]], [[mass shooting]] | status = | result = | side1 = [[Horse theft|horse thieves]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://oregonencyclopedia.org/articles/chinese_massacre_at_deep_creek/ |title=Chinese Massacre at Deep Creek |author=Nokes, Greg |date= |publisher=The Oregon Encyclopedia |accessdate=25 April 2018}}</ref> | side2 = Chinese gold-miners | side3 = | leadfigures1 = | leadfigures2 = | leadfigures3 = | howmany1 = 4-7 | howmany2 = 34 | howmany3 = | casualties1 = none | casualties2 = 10-34 | casualties3 = | fatalities = 10-34 | injuries = | arrests = 3 | detentions = | charged = none | fined = none | casualties_label = | notes = | sidebox = }} {{OSM Location map |coord={{Coord|46.158|-117.183}} |float=right |zoom=8 |width=300 |height=400 |scalemark=20 |shape1=n-circle |shape-color1=#f00 |shape-outline1=#fff |mark-size1=16 |mark-coord1 ={{Coord|45.7798|-116.6546}} |mark-title1 =Chinese Massacre Cove & Robinson Gulch (Chea Po) |mark-coord2 ={{Coord|45.807725|-116.688046}} |shape-color2=#00f |mark-title2 =Dug Bar (fording location) |mark-coord3 ={{Coord|45.55405|-116.52598}} |shape-color3=#080 |mark-title3 =Salt Creek (Lee She) |mark-coord4 ={{Coord|46.074708|-116.959846}} |shape4=n-cross |shape-color4=#000 |mark-title4 =Lime Point |mark-coord5 ={{Coord|46.667776|-117.432117}} |shape5=n-cross |shape-color5=#000 |mark-title5 =Log Cabin Island (now Lower Granite Dam) |mark-coord6 ={{Coord|46.704225|-117.688726}} |shape6=n-cross |shape-color6=#000 |mark-title6 =[[Penawawa, Washington]] |fullscreen-option=1 |caption=Locations in Hells Canyon |auto-caption=1 }} The '''Hells Canyon massacre''' (also known as the '''Snake River massacre''') was a [[massacre]] where thirty-four Chinese goldminers were ambushed and murdered in May 1887. In 2005, the area was renamed [[Chinese Massacre Cove]], and a memorial was placed there in 2012 in three languages, [[Standard Chinese|Chinese]], [[English language|English]], and [[Nez Perce language|Nez Perce]].
==Massacre== Two groups of Chinese miners, led by Chea Po and Lee She, departed [[Lewiston, Idaho|Lewiston]] in October 1886 and headed upriver along the [[Snake River|Snake]] into Oregon's [[Hells Canyon]] to search for gold. Chea's group stopped on the Oregon side of the Snake, near Robinson Gulch and the cove where Deep Creek empties into the Snake. Lee's group continued upriver to Salt Creek. Chea Po had chosen a location just upstream of Dug Bar, a [[ford (crossing)|ford]] used by horse and cattle thieves to cross the Snake.<ref name=Stratton />{{rp|115}} Dug Bar was named for Thomas J. Douglas, a thief who had used the area to graze his horses. Douglas was killed in 1883, and a gang led by Bruce Evans, known locally as "Old Blue", began using Douglas's abandoned cabin in the spring of 1887, approximately {{convert|1/2|mi}} downstream from Chea Po's camp. The gang consisted of Evans, J.T. ("Tigh") Canfield, C.O. (Homer) LaRue, Frank Vaughn, Carl (or Hezekiah) Hughes, Hiram Maynard and Robert McMillan, a fifteen-year-old boy.<ref name=Stratton />{{rp|115–116}}
In late May 1887 (May 25, according to Stratton)<ref name=Stratton />{{rp|116}} the gang of seven white [[horse gang]] members robbed, murdered, and mutilated between 10 and 34 Chinese employees of the [[Chinese Consolidated Benevolent Association#San Francisco|Sam Yup Company]], reportedly for their gold.<ref name=kgw>{{cite news |title=Next stop Qochyax Island |date=12 October 2005 |accessdate=12 March 2007 |website=KGW-TV |location=Portland, Oregon |agency=Associated Press |url=http://www.kgw.com/sharedcontent/APStories/stories/D8D6CD980.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070109192706/http://www.kgw.com/sharedcontent/APStories/stories/D8D6CD980.html |archivedate=9 January 2007 |deadurl=yes}}</ref><ref name=Scout88>{{cite news |url=https://oregonhistoryproject.org/articles/historical-records/news-article-the-chinese-murderers/ |title=The Chinese Murderers |author= |date=20 April 1888 |newspaper=Oregon Scout |accessdate=25 April 2018 |volume=IV |number=43}}</ref> Estimates of the value of gold stolen range from $4,000<ref name=Scout88 /> to $50,000.<ref name=NYT-AP95 /> According to a contemporaneous news article, the gold dust was given to Canfield for safekeeping, but he double-crossed the rest of the gang and fled the county.<ref name=Scout88 />
{{quote|text=The brutality of the Snake River atrocity was probably unexcelled, whether by whites or Indians, in all the anti-Chinese violence of the American West. After the first day's onslaught at Robinson Gulch, the killers wrecked and burned the camp and then threw the mutilated corpses into the Snake River. The bodies of the other Chinese received similar treatment. Since it was the high-water stage of the spring runoff, the dead Chinese were found for months (some accounts say for years) afterwards along the lower river.|author=David H. Stratton |source=''The Snake River Massacre of Chinese Miners, 1887'' (1983), p.117<ref name=Stratton>{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/stream/tasteofwestess00athe |title=A Taste of the West: essays in honor of Robert G. Athearn |date=1983 |editor=Smith, Duane A. |author=Stratton, David H. |chapter=The Snake River Massacre of Chinese Miners, 1887 |pages=109–129 |publisher=University of Colorado Press |isbn=9780871086419 |accessdate=25 April 2018}}</ref>}}
Robert McMillan made a [[deathbed confession]] to his father Hugh recounting details of the massacre, which were published in 1891. According to Hugh McMillan, the Chinese miners were ambushed by a party consisting of Robert McMillan, Bruce Evans, J.T. Canfield, Max Larue, and Frank Vaughn in late April 1887. Hiram Maynard and Carl Hughes were traveling with the others, but did not participate in the ambush. Canfield and Larue first attacked the camp of thirteen Chinese from the bluffs overlooking the cove, driving them towards Evans and Vaughn, who were in the path of their retreat. Twelve Chinese were killed in the initial fusillade, then the remaining man had "his brains beaten out", retrieving $5,500 in gold dust. The next day, eight more Chinese returned to the camp by boat, where the gang shot and killed them, throwing the 21 bodies into the Snake River. The gang then stole the boat and traveled {{convert|4|mi}} to the next Chinese camp, where they killed 13 more and retrieved $50,000 in gold. Hugh McMillan stated that Robert was only present for the first day's events, but the gang had discussed the next day's plans before Robert left the others.<ref name=McMillan>{{cite news |url=https://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SDU18910930.2.7 |title=Murdered for Gold |author=McMillan, Hugh |date=30 September 1891 |newspaper=Sacramento Daily Union |accessdate=25 April 2018}}</ref>
According to a modern account, Vaughn stayed behind to prepare dinner while the other six rode to ambush the miners. McMillan minded the horses; Canfield and LaRue shot from the rim of Robinson Gulch, while Evans shot from the river level; Hughes and Maynard were positioned upstream and downstream to catch any miner who tried to flee along the river. Their surprise attack was successful, and all ten of the miners at the camp were killed, the last with a rock after the gang had run out of ammunition.<ref name=Stratton />{{rp|116–117}} The gang returned to the Douglas cabin and restocked their ammunition; the next day, the Evans, Canfield, and LaRue ambushed a group of eight Chinese miners who returned to the cove, then sailed to a second camp and killed thirteen more miners.<ref name=Stratton />{{rp|117}}
===Aftermath=== The bodies of some murder victims began washing ashore soon afterward, swept downstream to places as far away as Lime Point (south of the mouth of the [[Grande Ronde River]]), Log Cabin Island (now the site of the [[Lower Granite Dam]]), and Penawawa, Washington. Each body bore unmistakable markings of great violence; J.K. Vincent, a federal official who investigated the crime, later wrote "every one was shot, cut up and stripped and thrown in the River."<ref name=Stratton />{{rp|117–118}} Lee She's group went to visit Chea Po's group at Robinson Gulch in early June 1887, and found three bodies in the deserted, ransacked camp; they fled in terror to Lewiston, where they reported the crimes.<ref name=Stratton />{{rp|119}}
A news article published in July 1887 called the corpses a "severe warning to Chinese miners" and blamed the victims: "More than likely it was the whites who look with an evil eye upon Chinese intrusion in American mines. The American miner kicks hard at the Chinese miner."<ref>{{cite news |url=https://oregonnews.uoregon.edu/lccn/sn97071028/1887-07-01/ed-1/seq-2/ |title=Headlines |author= |date=1 July 1887 |newspaper=The Lebanon Express |accessdate=27 April 2018}}</ref> Other local Chinese Americans believed that all Chinese miners along the Snake had been killed once the mutilated bodies began to surface.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://oregonnews.uoregon.edu/lccn/sn96061150/1887-07-13/ed-1/seq-2/ |title=Believed to Be True. |author= |date=13 July 1887 |newspaper=The Daily Astorian |accessdate=27 April 2018}}</ref> Initially, "a thorough investigation" described in a July 17, 1887 article concluded the Chinese had been murdered by rival Chinese miners, since the victims had been "shot in the back and mutilated by cleavers, a weapon in general use by the Chinese."<ref>{{cite news |url=https://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SBDC18870717.1.1 |title=Chinese Not Killed by Whites |author= |date=17 July 1887 |newspaper=San Bernardino Daily Courier |accessdate=25 April 2018}}</ref> George S. Craig owned the Douglas cabin and discovered numerous skeletons in the area when he returned to winter his stock in the fall of 1887.<ref name=Stratton />{{rp|118}}
Frank Vaughn confessed to the crime in 1888 and his testimony led to the indictment of the other six gang members on March 23, 1888.<ref name="OHS">{{cite journal |first=R. Gregory |last=Nokes |title=A Most Daring Outrage: Murders at Chinese Massacre Cove, 1887 |date=Fall 2006 |accessdate=20 March 2007 |work=Oregon Historical Quarterly |volume=107 |number=3 |url=http://www.ohs.org/research-and-library/oregon-historical-quarterly/upload/Nokes_A-Most-Daring-Outrage_OHQ-Fall-2006_107_3.pdf |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070128140548/http://www.historycooperative.org/journals/ohq/107.3/nokes.html |archivedate=28 January 2007 |deadurl=no}}</ref> In follow-up testimony given on April 16, Vaughn blamed Evans, Canfield, and LaRue for the massacre, and said that he, Hughes, Maynard, and McMillan had not participated.<ref name=OHS /> Vaughn himself was arrested on April 18. By the time he was arrested, almost the entire gang had left America, save Vaughn and Hughes.<ref name=Scout88 />
{{quote box |quote=I guess if they had killed 31 white men something would have been done about it, but none of the jury knew the Chinamen or cared much about it, so they turned the men loose.|author= —George S. Craig |source=undated newspaper interview<ref name=Stratton />{{rp|125}} |width = 15em |align=right}}
Three of the gang (Maynard, McMillan, and Hughes)<ref name=OHS /> were brought to trial but none were convicted.<ref name=uw>{{cite web |url=http://www.washington.edu/uwired/outreach/cspn/Website/Classroom%20Materials/Pacific%20Northwest%20History/Lessons/Lesson%2015/15.html |title=Lesson Fifteen: Industrialization, Class, and Race: Chinese and the Anti-Chinese Movement in the Late 19th-Century Northwest |publisher=History of Washington State & the Pacific Northwest, Center for Study of the Pacific Northwest |website=University of Washington. |accessdate=12 March 2007 |author= |date=}}</ref><ref name=Nokes09>{{cite book |url=http://osupress.oregonstate.edu/book/massacred-for-gold |author=Nokes, R. Gregory |date=2009 |title=Massacred for Gold: The Chinese in Hells Canyon |location=Corvallis, Oregon |publisher=Oregon State University Press1 |isbn=978-0-87071-570-9 |accessdate=25 April 2018}}</ref>{{rp|179–181}} The trio were arraigned on August 28, 1888, and pleaded not guilty on August 29. Their testimony was consistent with Vaughn's, namely, that blame for the crime fell squarely on Evans, Canfield, and LaRue, all absent.<ref name=Stratton />{{rp|124}} The jury found the three men innocent on September 1, 1888, following a short trial.<ref name=OHS />
* J.T. Canfield was imprisoned in [[Kansas]] for stealing mules and returned to [[Wallowa County, Oregon|Wallowa County]] to search for gold after his release. He was noted to be in the area during the trial, and moved to [[Texas]] before settling in [[Idaho]] and opening a [[blacksmith]] shop as Charley Canfield.<ref name=OHS /> * Bruce Evans was arrested within a week of the massacre on an unrelated [[rustling]] charge. He escaped from custody two weeks later, possibly with the help of Hughes and Vaughn. When he fled, he left two children and his wife behind. His name is engraved on a [[memorial arch]] in the courthouse square of [[Enterprise, Oregon]], honoring the early pioneers of the county.<ref name=OHS /> * C.O. LaRue was rumored to have died in a dispute over a card game in [[California]].<ref name=Stratton /><ref name=OHS /> * Robert McMillan died of [[diphtheria]] in 1888 at the age of 16.<ref name=Stratton /><ref name=McMillan /><ref name=OHS />
==Legacy== In 1995, Charlotte McIver discovered a cache of documents relating to the 1888 trial in an old safe being donated to the Wallowa County Museum.<ref name=NYT-AP95 /> When the news came to the attention of R. Gregory Nokes, a reporter for ''The Oregonian'', he began his own research into the massacre, going on to publish a journal article in 2006 and a nonfiction book in 2009 after his retirement in 2003 allowed him to conduct research full-time.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/O/index.ssf/2010/01/osu_press_book_recounts_chines.html |title=OSU Press book recounts Chinese massacre in Wallowa County |author=Terry, John |date=24 January 2010 |newspaper=The Oregonian |accessdate=25 April 2018}}</ref>
The five acre site was named Chinese Massacre Cove in 2005<ref name=usgs>{{cite web |url=http://geonames.usgs.gov/docs/minutes/DNCOct05Minutes.pdf |title=Committee meeting minutes - October 12, 2005 |publisher=U.S. Board on Geographic Names, Domestic Names Committee, U.S. Geological Survey |date=October 12, 2005 |accessdate=12 March 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060420050441/http://geonames.usgs.gov/docs/minutes/DNCOct05Minutes.pdf |archivedate=20 April 2006 |deadurl=yes}}</ref> over the objections of Wallowa County commissioners.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nwasianweekly.com/2009/07/historians-track-chinese-history-in-idaho/ |title=Historians track Chinese history in Idaho |author=Bauer, Jennifer K. |date=23 July 2009 |newspaper=Northwest Asian Weekly |accessdate=27 April 2018 |agency=The Associated Press}}</ref> The Chinese Massacre Memorial Committee placed a granite monument measuring {{convert|4|by|5|ft}} in May 2012,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/pacific-northwest-news/index.ssf/2011/11/slain_chinese_gold_miners_will.html |title=Massacred Chinese gold miners to receive memorial along Snake River |author=Cockle, Richard |date=26 November 2011 |newspaper=The Oregonian |accessdate=25 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=152301945 |title=Chopper Delivers Memorial Marker To Massacre Site |author=Banse, Tom |date=8 May 2012 |work=npr |accessdate=27 April 2018}}</ref> engraved with the words "Chinese Massacre Cove. Site of the 1887 massacre of as many as 34 Chinese gold miners. No one was held accountable" written in English, Chinese, and Nez Perce. It was dedicated on June 22, 2012.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://inland360.com/books/2012/05/massacre-in-hells-canyon-to-be-marked-in-stone-at-chinese-remembering-2012/ |title=Massacre in Hells Canyon to be marked in stone at Chinese Remembering 2012 |author=Bauer, Jennifer K |date=15 May 2012 |work=Inland 360 |accessdate=27 April 2018}}</ref>
[[Deep Creek (2010 novel)|''Deep Creek'']], a fictionalized account of the massacre and its aftermath written by [[William Howarth]] and [[Anne Matthews]] under the [[pen name]] "Dana Hand",<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dana-hand.com/authors.html|title=Authors {{!}} Dana Hand|last=|first=|date=|website=dana-hand.com|publisher=|access-date=25 April 2018}}</ref> was selected by [[The Washington Post]] as one of the best [[novels]] of 2010.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/12/10/AR2010121003240.html|title=The best novels of 2010|last=|first=|date=10 December 2010 |newspaper=The Washington Post |publisher=|access-date=25 April 2018}}</ref>
Two episodes of the television show [[Ghost Mine (TV series)|''Ghost Mine'']], first aired in October 2013, covered the investigation of paranormal activity at Chinese Massacre Cove.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://portlandtribune.com/wlt/96-opinion/195009-local-authors-take-on-syfy-ghost-mine-show |title=Local authors take on Syfy 'Ghost Mine' show |author=Nokes, Greg |date=19 September 2013 |newspaper=Portland Tribune |accessdate=27 April 2018}}</ref>
[[Peter Ludwin]] wrote and published a collection of poetry in 2016, ''Gone to Gold Mountain''. He states he was inspired after reading ''Massacred for Gold'', the 2009 book by R. Gregory Nokes.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/books/index.ssf/2016/09/gone_to_gold_mountain_peter_lu.html |title=Chinese gold miners killed in Hells Canyon are remembered in new poetry collection |author=Wang, Amy |date=13 September 2016 |newspaper=The Oregonian |accessdate=25 April 2018}}</ref>
