{{infobox ethnic group | group = Kami/Bishwakarma | native_name = कामी/विश्वकर्मा | native_name_lang = nep | image = | image_caption = | poptime = | population = | region1 = {{flag|Nepal}} | pop1 = 1,258,554 (4.8% of Nepal's population)<ref name="cbs"/> | region2 = [[India]], [[Bhutan]] and [[Burma]] | langs = [[Nepali language]] (Khas kura) | rels = [[File:Om.svg|20px]][[Hinduism]], [[Budhism]], [[Christianity]] | related = [[Khas people]], [[Damai]], [[Badi people|Badi]], [[Sarki (ethnic group)|Sarki]], [[Gandarbha|Gandarbha/Gaine]] }} '''Kami'''/'''Bishwakarma''' (Nepali: कामी/ विश्वकर्मा) is an ethno-linguistic [[Indo-Aryan languages|Indo-Aryan]] [[Nepali language|Nepali]] speaking group. It is a [[Khas]] occupational caste belonging to blacksmiths.{{sfn|Whelpton|2005|p=31}} The 1854 Nepalese Muluki Ain (Legal Code) not keep in lowest category.<ref>Gurung, Harka (2005) Social Exclusion and Maoist Insurgency. Paper presented at National Dialogue Conference at ILO Convention 169 on Indigenous and Tribal peoples, Kathmandu, 19–20 January 2005.</ref> Kami are categorized under "Hill [[Dalit]]" among the 9 broad social groups, along with [[Damai]], [[Badi people|Badi]], [[Sarki (ethnic group)|Sarki]] and [[Gandarbha|Gaine]] by the Government of Nepal.<ref name="cbs"/> Thus, the tribal designation of [[Khas]] is given only in few context to Kami{{sfn|Whelpton|2005|p=31}}
They live in Nepal, [[Sikkim]] and [[Darjeeling District]] of [[West Bengal]], [[India]]. Kamis are essentially blacksmiths Kami/Vishowkarma are Vishowkarmabramin.are scattered across almost all hilly districts of Nepal, districts of Sikkim, Darjeeling (a District of W.B), and [[Assam]]; some have settled in other parts of India as well. They are also known as Vishwakarma or Bishwakarma.
The Kami are traditionally held to be the descendants of God or [[Vishvakarman|Lord Vishwakarma]]. They are one sub-caste from other Vishwakarma sub-caste to kami they have their own identity and occupation and language. The word ''kami'' may derive from the Sanskrit word ''karma'' or ''kam'', meaning "work". The Kami make the famous [[Khukuri]] knives used by the [[Gurkha]] Army, and a traditional Nepali drum called a [[Madal]]. They are also expert performers of the traditional folk dance ''[[Maruni]] Nritya''.
According to the 2001 Nepal census, there were a total of 895,954 Kami, of whom 96.69% were [[Hindu]]s and 2.21% were [[Buddhist]]s. According to [[2011 Nepal census]], Kami make up 4.8% of Nepal's population (or 12,58,554 peoples).<ref name="cbs">{{Cite web|URL=https://unstats.un.org/unsD/demographic/sources/census/wphc/Nepal/Nepal-Census-2011-Vol1.pdf|title=Nepal Census 2011}}</ref>
