{{Infobox language |name=Tumak |states=[[Chad]] |region=Southwest |speakers=25,000 |date=1993 census |ref=e18 |familycolor=Afro-Asiatic |fam2=[[Chadic languages|Chadic]] |fam3=[[East Chadic languages|East Chadic]] |fam4=[[East Chadic A languages|East Chadic A]] |fam5=[[Sibine languages|Sibine]] (A.1.1) |iso3=tmc |glotto=tuma1260 |glottorefname=Tumak |dia1=Tumak |dia2=Motun |dia3=Mawer }}
'''Tumak''', also known as '''Toumak''', '''Tumag''', '''Tummok''', '''Sara Toumak''', '''Tumac''', and '''Dije''', is an [[Afro-Asiatic languages|Afro-Asiatic]] language spoken in the southwestern [[Chad]]ian prefectures of [[Moyen-Chari Prefecture|Moyen-Chari]] and [[Koumra]]. Motun (Mod) and Tumak dialects have a [[lexical similarity]] of only 70%;<ref name="e18"/> Blench (2006) lists Tumak, Motun, and Mawer as separate languages.<ref>Blench, 2006. [http://rogerblench.info/Language/Afroasiatic/General/AALIST.pdf The Afro-Asiatic Languages: Classification and Reference List] (ms)</ref> Most Motun speakers use some [[Sara languages|Sara]].<ref name="e18"/>
The "Gulei" listed in Greenberg might be a dialect of Tumak.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=xogHAQAAIAAJ&q=gulei+chadic&dq=gulei+chadic&hl=en&sa=X&ei=b6omUueTAqGCiwL1ooBI&ved=0CD0Q6AEwAw Chadic Newsletter]</ref>
