{{Infobox language |name=Vilela |nativename= |states=[[Argentina]] |extinct=20 by 1981;<ref>{{e16|vil}}</ref> gone by 2011 |ref=e18 |familycolor=American |fam1=[[Lule–Vilela languages|Lule–Vilela]] |iso3=vil |glotto=vile1241 |glottorefname=Vilela }}
'''Vilela''' (''Uakambalelté, Atalalá, Chulupí~Chunupí'')<ref>Not to be confused with [[Nivaclé language|Niwaklé]], which is also called Chulupí~Chunupí.</ref> is an extinct language last spoken in the [[Resistencia, Chaco|Resistencia]] area of [[Argentina]] and in the eastern [[Gran Chaco|Chaco]] near the [[Paraguayan]] border. Dialects were ''Ocol, Chinipi, Sinipi''; only Ocol survives. The people call themselves ''Waqha-umbaβelte'' 'Waqha speakers'.
The last Vilela people were absorbed into the surrounding [[Toba people]] and [[Spanish language|Spanish]]-speaking townsfolk.
==Phonology== Vilela appears to have the five vowels of Spanish and approximately the following consonants:
{|class="wikitable IPA" |- |m||n|| || |- |b||d||dʒ||ɡ |- |p||t||tʃ||k||ʔ |- |pʼ||tʼ||tʃʼ||kʼ |- |f||s||ʃ||x |- | ||ɬ|| || |- |w||l||j|| |- | ||r|| || |}
